== History == The exact date of the shrine's founding is unknown. However, its former {{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|12=draft|12=draft}}, "Sanmyōin," was established during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|12=draft|12=draft}}, leading to speculation that the shrine was founded around the same time. Sanmyōin was a temple of the {{ill|Honzan-ha|ja|本山派|12=draft|12=draft}} sect of {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|12=draft|12=draft}}, but it was abolished during the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|12=draft|12=draft}} reforms of the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="jinja">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1998, pp. 324–325.</ref>
In 1873, under the Modern Shrine Ranking System, Raiden Shrine was designated as a "Village Shrine" (村社). In 1886, it absorbed the {{ill|Hikawa Shrine|ja|氷川神社|12=draft|12=draft}} previously managed by Sanmyōin as its bettō-ji.<ref name="jinja"></ref> The shrine's torii plaque now bears the inscriptions "Raiden Shrine (right)" and "Hikawa Shrine (left)," reflecting this historical merger.
== Access == * Approximately 6 minutes on foot from {{ill|Kombu Station|ja|今羽駅|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== References == {{reflist}}
== Bibliography == * Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1998.
