{{infobox shinto shrine| image=Raiden Jinja (Kita, Saitama).JPG}} '''Raiden Shrine''' (雷電神社, Raiden Jinja) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Kita-ku, Saitama|ja|北区 (さいたま市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Saitama City, Saitama Prefecture. It enshrines {{ill|Raijin|ja|雷神|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Ōraijin) and {{ill|Susanoo|ja|素盞嗚尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and is classified as a former {{ill|Sonsha|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the Modern Shrine Ranking System.
== History == The exact date of the shrine's founding is unknown. However, its former {{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, "Sanmyōin," was established during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, leading to speculation that the shrine was founded around the same time. Sanmyōin was a temple of the {{ill|Honzan-ha|ja|本山派|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} sect of {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, but it was abolished during the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} reforms of the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="jinja">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1998, pp. 324–325.</ref>
In 1873, under the Modern Shrine Ranking System, Raiden Shrine was designated as a "Village Shrine" (村社). In 1886, it absorbed the {{ill|Hikawa Shrine|ja|氷川神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} previously managed by Sanmyōin as its bettō-ji.<ref name="jinja"></ref> The shrine's torii plaque now bears the inscriptions "Raiden Shrine (right)" and "Hikawa Shrine (left)," reflecting this historical merger.
== Access == * Approximately 6 minutes on foot from {{ill|Kombu Station|ja|今羽駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== References == {{reflist}}
== Bibliography == * Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1998.
