{{Infobox religious building|image=File:Raiden Jinja (Kita, Saitama).JPG|prefecture={{ill|Kita-ku, Saitama|qid=Q542542}}|coordinates={{Coord|35.953944444444446|N|139.61958333333334|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}}}{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q114641791]] Wikidata name: (none) [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 08:55, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{infobox shinto shrine| image=Raiden Jinja (Kita, Saitama).JPG}} '''Raiden Shrine''' (雷電神社, Raiden Jinja) is a Shinto shrine located in [[:en:Kita-ku, Saitama|Kita-ku, Saitama]], Saitama City, Saitama Prefecture. It enshrines [[:en:Raijin|Raijin]] (Ōraijin) and {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素盞嗚尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スサノオ}} and is classified as a former {{ill|Sonsha|ja|村社|1=Son-sha|qid=Q134917284}}{{efn|Former shrine rank|lt=Son-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sonsha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}} under the Modern Shrine Ranking System.
== History == The exact date of the shrine's founding is unknown. However, its former {{ill|Bettō-ji|ja|別当寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bettō-ji|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, "Sanmyōin," was established during the [[:en:Sengoku period|Sengoku period]], leading to speculation that the shrine was founded around the same time. Sanmyōin was a temple of the {{ill|Honzan-ha|ja|本山派|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honzan-ha|qq=|1=Honzan-ha|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11520192}} sect of [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendō]], but it was abolished during the [[:en:Shinbutsu bunri|Shinbutsu bunri]] reforms of the early [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]].<ref name="jinja">Saitama Prefecture Shrine Research Group, ''Saitama no Jinja: Kita-Adachi, Kodama, Minami-Saitama,'' Saitama Shrine Bureau, 1998, pp. 324–325.</ref>
In 1873, under the Modern Shrine Ranking System, Raiden Shrine was designated as a "Village Shrine" (村社). In 1886, it absorbed the [[:en:Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine]] previously managed by Sanmyōin as its bettō-ji.<ref name="jinja"></ref> The shrine's torii plaque now bears the inscriptions "Raiden Shrine (right)" and "Hikawa Shrine (left)," reflecting this historical merger.
== Access == * Approximately 6 minutes on foot from [[:en:Komba Station|Kombu Station]].
